how to make my background catch a 404:
Great question — to **catch a `404` (or any HTTP error)** in `background.js` using `fetch`, you need to manually check the `response.ok` or `response.status`, because:

> `fetch` does **not throw an error** for HTTP errors like 404 or 500 — it only throws for **network errors** (e.g., DNS failure, offline).

---

### ✅ Here’s how to properly catch and handle a 404 in `background.js`:

```js
chrome.runtime.onMessage.addListener((request, sender, sendResponse) => {
  if (request.from === "content" && request.name) {
    const apiUrl = `https://api.agify.io?name=${encodeURIComponent(request.name)}`;

    (async function () {
      try {
        const response = await fetch(apiUrl);

        // Check for HTTP status
        if (!response.ok) {
          throw new Error(`HTTP error! Status: ${response.status}`);
        }

        const data = await response.json();

        chrome.tabs.sendMessage(sender.tab.id, {
          from: "background",
          apiData: data
        });
      } catch (error) {
        console.error("❌ Fetch failed or HTTP error:", error.message);

        chrome.tabs.sendMessage(sender.tab.id, {
          from: "background",
          apiData: { error: error.message }
        });
      }
    })();

    return true;
  }
});
```

