make the YouTube-transcript file:
Here’s how you can make the `YouTube-transcript` module yourself. This version **scrapes the YouTube transcript using the `fetch` API** and parses the result.

It works by hitting the YouTube's `timedtext` endpoint, which is used for fetching caption tracks.

---

### 📁 `YouTube-transcript.js` — Transcript Scraper Module

```javascript
export class YoutubeTranscript {
    /**
     * Fetch transcript using YouTube video ID
     * @param {string} videoId
     * @returns {Promise<Array<{start: string, dur: string, text: string}>>}
     */
    static async fetchTranscript(videoId) {
        const transcriptUrl = `https://video.google.com/timedtext?lang=en&v=${videoId}`;

        const response = await fetch(transcriptUrl);
        if (!response.ok) {
            throw new Error(`Failed to fetch transcript: ${response.statusText}`);
        }

        const xml = await response.text();
        return YoutubeTranscript.parseTranscriptXML(xml);
    }

    /**
     * Parse XML transcript response
     * @param {string} xmlText
     * @returns {Array<{start: string, dur: string, text: string}>}
     */
    static parseTranscriptXML(xmlText) {
        const parser = new DOMParser();
        const xml = parser.parseFromString(xmlText, "application/xml");

        const texts = Array.from(xml.getElementsByTagName("text"));

        return texts.map(node => ({
            start: node.getAttribute("start"),
            dur: node.getAttribute("dur"),
            text: node.textContent.replace(/&#39;/g, "'").replace(/&quot;/g, '"'),
        }));
    }
}
```

---

### ✅ How to Use

```javascript
import { YoutubeTranscript } from './YouTube-transcript.js';

YoutubeTranscript.fetchTranscript("dQw4w9WgXcQ")
  .then(transcript => {
    transcript.forEach(line => {
      console.log(`[${line.start}] ${line.text}`);
    });
  })
  .catch(err => console.error(err));
```

---

### 🛑 Caveats
- This only works if the video has an **English transcript** (`lang=en`). You can change the `lang` to another code like `es`, `fr`, etc.
- Auto-generated captions also usually work.
- This doesn't work for **manually disabled or copyrighted** videos.

